EPS Short Reflections | The attribution crisis in LLM search results: Estimating ecosystem exploitation

Prompt: Where does this validate or challenge Cypher's data sovereignty stance?

Response: 

This really validate our point about data sovereignty that we write about weekly. The use of LLMs is not theoretically extractive.
Under the framework that websites, and databases are "workers" the LLM is "stealing" extracting value with compensation, in the
case of the internet that is a "social contract" of citation. 

This is a systemic error not a random one when it occurs, its a design issue AKA a choice by humans. I believe I can :
		a - design nonextractive AI tools
		b - measure the attribution gap of exisiting tools
		c - write about Ai policy with a focus on attribution and drive actual ROI on operational work, rather than generating/ 
producing.


Key Insight| Advancing the auditing and monitoring of AI systems and the QA of their attribution gap (Ecosystem Exploitation)

Why it matters? The knowledge is sythesized for value with on citation. This is extraction and exploitation, given there is no attribution of 
credit for the knowledge. 

The attribution crisis. 15.6% of LLM responses involved no website visits despite being in search
mode, yet 30% provided no citations whatsoever—a substantial gap between content consumption and
content recognition. This pattern varies dramatically by provider; 39% of responses show perfect
attribution alignment (zero gap), while 61% exhibit some degree of ecosystem exploitation. For Gemini,
a “zero” gap still tends to signal exploitation though, because the model usually answers without visiting
any external site even when its Google search tool is enabled

3-exploitations patterns
		No search - relying on pretrained data, zero search/ no RAG/ RAG with no disclosure of citation (occurrs 15%-35%)
		No citiation - typically an issue with the model not the query; deeply impact SEO with no accountablity 
		High Volution, low credit - a high volume of queried sites, but only citing a small percentage (Perplexity suffers from this)

We need access to: 
		Search trace
		citaction logs
		standardized telemtry

Methodology to Adopt in QA measurement of AI RAG systems
How we measure the attribution gap: 
- we want to measure 
occurences - logistic regression x Hurdle Model (binary model)
intensity - read list vs the citation list = output is the gap 
- the questions:
		1. is their a gap? 
		2. how large is the gap?  

